{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-12-07","name":"Nicholas de Soules","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Nicholas de Soules","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Nicholas"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Soules"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1200–1264","fullLifespan":"1200–1264","portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/g50gh/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"memoryArtifacts":[{"memoryType":"PHOTO","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-904-88935-3396-94/dist.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/80323689","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-904-88935-3396-94/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-904-88935-3396-94/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","@type":"ImageObject"}],"birthDate":"+1200","birthPlace":{"address":"Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland","geo":{"latitude":55.2,"longitude":-2.75,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1264","deathPlace":{"address":"Seine Inferieure, Normandie, France","geo":{"latitude":49.75,"longitude":1.0,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\nNicholas Soulis was the son of Fulco Soulis. He succeeded his father sometime before 1227.\n\nIn 1237, Nicholas was appointed as sheriff of Roxburgh. Some say that about 1240-2, he started the construction of Hermitage Castle on the then border with England. Historians agree, as it was not on Soulis land, that it was most likely built by Walter Comyn, Earl of Menteith, and that the Soulis family had little to do with the castle until the end of the century.\n\nHe married Annora de Normanville, daughter of John de Normanville, sometime before 1244 when the King of England restored Nicholas and his wife to the lands they had held at Stamfordham and Stokesfeud, in Northumberland. These lands had belonged to Annora's father, John de Normanville.\n\nIn 1264, Nicholas -- knight, hereditary butler of Scotland, and Lord of Liddesdale, described in a Scottish chronicle as \"the wisest and most eloquent man in the whole kingdom\" -- died at Rouen, Normandy. He was succeeded by his son, William.\n\n«b»Nicholas and Annora had the following issue:«/b»\n1.) William I de Soules of Liddesdale (died circa 1292), married Ermengarde Durward, had issue.\n\n2.) John de Soules of Old Roxburgh (died 1310), married Margaret de Ardross, had issue.\n\n3.) Thomas de Soules of Stamfordham (died circa 1304), married Alicia de Mulcastre.\n\n«b»Legends«/b»\nFrom the beginning, Hermitage was seen as a vitally important base for controlling Liddesdale in the Scottish West March and a large stretch of the Border with England. Indeed, the castle's construction, probably by Sir Nicholas de Soules, butler to King William, in about 1240, almost brought the two countries to war. De Soules' fortress was probably a motte-and-bailey castle similar to his ancestors' former stronghold, Liddel Castle, four miles to the south beside Liddel Water at Old Castleton.\n\nFrom the Hermitage Castle website, www.undiscoveredscotland.co.uk/hawick/hermitagecastle/ : \"A wooden castle was first built on this spot in 1242 by Sir Nicholas de Soules, butler to the King of Scotland and a man whose reputation included witchcraft, child abduction, and murder. De Soules allegedly came to a sticky end when oppressed locals rose up and boiled him in molten lead.\"\n\n«b»NOTE: «/b»\nThere is also a story about Nicholas's ancestor (probably Ranulf/Randolph de Soules, d. 1208), who was supposedly murdered by his servants because he was so vile. Either they were the same incident (with confusion over which person was involved), or there was a real \"mean\" streak running in this family.","sourceList":[{"title":"Wikipedia-Nicholas II de Soules","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_II_de_Soules","sourceUri":"3BF6-NSQ"},{"title":"Nicholas Soules - Wiki Tree","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Soules-72","sourceUri":"S8DF-TGZ"},{"title":"Sir Nicholas de Soules - Geneanet","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://gw.geneanet.org/natoab?lang=en&iz=0&p=sir+nicholas&n=de+soules&oc=1","sourceUri":"S8DF-TFC"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1200","date":"1200","place":"Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1222","date":"Aft 1222","place":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","age":"23","id":"LHXC-TBC"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1240","date":"Abt 1240","place":"Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland","age":"40","id":"GZKP-QW9"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1240","date":"1240","place":"Castleton, Roxburghshire, Scotland","age":"40","id":"GVBP-9TD"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1245","date":"about 1245","place":"Hermitage Castle.Liddesdale,Roxburghshire,Scotland","age":"45","id":"LKPJ-NTL"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1247","date":"1247","place":"Liddisdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland","age":"47","id":"LJRT-RLQ"},{"name":"Death","sources":"1","year":"1264","date":"1264","place":"Seine Inferieure, Normandie, France","age":"64"}],"parent":[{"name":"Fulco de Soules Lord of Liddesdale","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1175–1222","birthDate":"A+1175","deathDate":"+1222/","age":48,"portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/ozyvj/thumb64.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"@type":"Person","identifier":"LHXC-TBC","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/LHXC-TBC/fulco-de-soules-lord-of-liddesdale-1175-1222","published":true},{"name":"Mrs. Fulco de Soules","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1176–Female","birthDate":"A+1176","@type":"Person","identifier":"GKNZ-YQ4","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GK